<sections.2>
Apoptosis induction by androgen withdrawal in normal and hormone-dependent malignant prostate involves the transforming growth factor-²1 (-²1) signalling pathway (yprianou and saacs, 1989). ecent immunohistochemical analysis of  tissue revealed an increase in -²1 expression but no change in -² receptor (²) in patients who had undergone treatment with the clinically used quinazoline-based ±1-adrenoceptor antagonist terazosin (lassman et al, 2001). he -²1 signalling system normally functions to inhibit proliferation and induce apoptosis of epithelial and endothelial cells (assague et al, 2000); its signal transduction pathway involves the receptor-mediated activation by phosphorylation of the intracellular effectors, mad2, mad3 and mad4, and their translocation to the nucleus where they regulate gene transcription (assague, 2000). xpression and activation of these intracellular effectors of the -²1 pathway are critical to the execution of the apoptotic process (e. Caestecker et al, 2000). An inhibitory regulator of TGF-Ξ²1 signalling, Smad7, (Whitman, 1997) is regulated by TGF-Ξ²1 specifically via Smad3 and Smad4 indicating a negative feedback mechanism (Hayashi et al, 1997). Smad7 is induced during apoptosis of prostate epithelial cells (Brodin et al, 1999) and has recently been shown to sensitise other cell types to apoptosis (Mazars et al, 2001; Schiffer et al, 2001).
