revious studies have demonstrated that the piperizidinyl quinazoline-based ±1-adrenoceptor antagonists doxazosin and terazosin (igure 1) induce apoptosis in prostate cancer cells, whereas the methoxysulphonamide-derived ±1-adrenoceptor antagonist tamsulosin had no apoptotic function (yprianou and enning, 2000). aspases as apoptosis executioners upon sequential activation can cleave protein substrates leading to apoptotic cell death (ohen, 1997). o determine the involvement of the caspase cascade in ±1-adrenoceptor antagonist-mediated apoptosis and the observed differences in apoptotic capability between these two structurally dissimilar drugs, we investigated the activation of caspase-3 in prostate cancer cells treated with either doxazosin or tamsulosin. estern blotting revealed the temporal induction of caspase-3 (17β€‰k. Da) in doxazosin-treated cells after 9β€‰h, an effect that was maintained up to 24β€‰h (Figure 2AFigure 2Effect of doxazosin on caspase-3 activation in prostate cancer cells. PC-3 prostate cancer cells were cultured and treated with either doxazosin (25β€‰ΞΌM) or tamsulosin (25β€‰ΞΌM) for 0, 3, 6, 9, 12 and 24β€‰h. Cell lysates (40β€‰ΞΌg protein) were subjected to Western blotting as described in β€�Materials and Methodsβ€™. The expression and activation of caspase-3 in response to doxazosin (panel A) and tamsulosin (panel B) treatment is shown. Molecular weight sizes are indicated on the right.). The activated form of caspase-3 was not detected in tamsulosin-treated prostate cancer cells (Figure 2B), consistent with the inability of this compound to induce apoptosis (Kyprianou and Benning, 2000).
