<sections.7>
D
he ability of quinazoline-derived ±1-adrenoceptor antagonists to induce apoptosis in human prostate cancer cells via an ±1-adrenoceptor-independent mechanism has been established (yprianou and enning, 2000; enning and yprianou, 2002). he present study focused on dissecting the molecular mechanism underlying this action. ur findings demonstrate that caspase-3 was activated in response to doxazosin and not tamsulosin, evidence confirming the apoptotic nature of the action of quinazoline-derived ±1-adrenoceptor antagonists against prostate cell growth. his induction was first evident within 9β€‰h of treatment and was maintained up to 24β€‰h, a pattern that temporally correlates with the morphological manifestations of apoptosis in prostate cancer cells following doxazosin treatment (yprianou and enning, 2000).
-²1 has recently been shown to activate caspase-3 to induce apoptosis in the -154 prostate epithelial cell line (hipuk et al, 2001), evidence supporting our hypothesis that doxazosin may activate apoptosis of prostate cancer cells through -²1 signalling. oxazosin resulted in a β€�latentβ€™ induction of -²1 m. RNA expression that was subsequent to a moderate increase in the active TGF-Ξ²1 levels by prostate cancer cells PC-3 (after 24β€‰h of treatment). While a similar pattern has been exhibited by apoptotic T-cells with an enhanced release of active TGF-Ξ²1 without major changes in the mRNA expression (Chen et al, 2001), one may also consider the possibility that the observed upregulation of TGF-Ξ² mRNA in prostate cancer cells could be a consequence of doxazosin-induced apoptosis. The lack of induction of TΞ²RII expression in prostate cancer cells by doxazosin is consistent with our earlier report indicating no changes in TΞ²RII protein levels in prostate tissue (from BPH patients) after treatment with the quinazolines (Glassman et al, 2001). It appears that doxazosin modulated the expression of the intracellular effectors TGF-Ξ²1 signalling pathway, Smad4 and Smad7 proteins, towards activation of the apoptotic machinery.
Microarray-based examination of doxazosin mediated-gene expression revealed the rapid upregulation of two TGF-Ξ²1-modulated genes, IΞΊBΞ± and p21WAF-1. Doxazosin-induced over-expression of IΞΊBΞ± may have implications for NF-ΞΊB intracellular signalling. For instance, in prostate cancer cells and metastatic melanoma cells, the blockade of NF-ΞΊB by a nondegradable dominant-negative IΞΊBΞ± mutant suppresses angiogenesis, invasion and metastasis (Huang et al, 2000,2001), and may reduce the apoptotic effects associated with NF-ΞΊB signalling (Baldwin, 1996). These reports together with the observed upregulation of IΞΊBΞ± in prostate cancer cells may provide a mechanism to explain the increased apoptosis and reduced tumour vascularity in prostate cancer specimens (Keledjian et al, 2001). Constitutive activation of NF-ΞΊB has been reported in many tumours (Baldwin, 1996), including androgen-independent prostate cancer cells (Pajonk et al, 1999; Palayoor et al, 1999; Suh et al, 2002) and oestrogen receptor-negative breast cancer cells (Biswas et al, 2001). This activation of NF-ΞΊB survival signalling is believed to provide a growth advantage in androgen-independent prostate cancer cells by suppressing apoptosis and inducing cell adhesion and angiogenic potential (Huang et al, 2001; Gasparian et al, 2002).
Smad4 is the principal intracellular effector of TGF-Ξ²1 signalling and its expression is regulated at the protein and mRNA level by doxazosin in PC-3 cells. The mechanism may involve the inhibition of Smad4 degradation, recently reported to be mediated by the oncogenic Ras pathway. Blockade of the oncogenic Ras pathway using a quinazoline-based tyrosine kinase inhibitor (TKI) PD98059 restores Smad4 expression levels and TGF-Ξ²1 signalling in vitro (Saha et al, 2001). Upregulation of Smad4 would also facilitate the transcription of several TGF-Ξ²1-regulated genes such as Smad7 (Von Gersdorff et al, 2000). While Smad7 is induced during androgen-withdrawal-induced apoptosis in prostate cells (Brodin et al, 1999), Smad7 induction has also been shown to antagonise directly TGF-Ξ²1 signalling (Whitman, 1997). Considering the evidence that Smad7-mediated apoptosis functionally involves inhibition of NF-ΞΊB nuclear signalling (Lallemand et al, 2001; Schiffer et al, 2001) and in view of the present observations that IΞΊBΞ± is upregulated within 6β€“24β€‰h, preceding the induction of Smad7 (observed at 48β€‰h of treatment), one may suggest that doxazosin may indeed have inhibitory effects on NF-ΞΊB signalling pathway, by inducing IΞΊBΞ±, an action that subsequently triggers apoptosis.
TIEG1 is an early TGF-Ξ²1 upregulated transcription factor that has been documented to regulate apoptosis in several tumour cell lines. The role of this nuclear factor has not yet been characterised in prostate growth, but it might potentially involve the activation of proapoptotic mechanisms, such as the downregulation of bcl-2 as reported in lung epithelial cells (Chalaux et al, 1999).
The Ξ±1-adrenoceptor antagonists doxazosin and terazosin share structural similarities with particular TKIs owing to the presence of a quinazoline ring (Figure 1). It is thus of major interest that several quinazoline-based chemicals have been demonstrated to compete with ATP binding to protein tyrosine kinases to inhibit various intracellular signalling pathways (Rewcastle et al, 1995). The mechanism of action for quinazoline-based TKI involves prevention of the transmembrane tyrosine kinase phosphorylation by competing with the ATP-binding site on the receptor (Arteaga et al, 1997). The presence of this component may provide additional valuable insights into the molecular mechanisms for Ξ±1-adrenoceptor antagonist-mediated apoptotic action in tumour cells (Anglin et al, 2002). Considering this evidence, one can speculate on the potential function of the intrinsic quinazoline component to confer partial TKI activity to these drugs, a unique structural characteristic with potentially significant pharmacological dimensions that warrant further investigation. Moreover, a potential antiangiogenic effect of terazosin and doxazosin against prostate tumours has been demonstrated in both in vitro and in clinical prostate specimens (Chon et al, 1999; Keledjian et al, 2001; Keledjian and Kyprianou, 2003). This action is believed to be mediated by quinazoline-induced anoikis and inhibition of cell invasion (Keledjian and Kyprianou, 2003).
In conclusion, we have demonstrated that doxazosin-mediated apoptosis in prostate cancer cells involves activation of latent apoptotic machinery via effectors of TGF-Ξ²1 signalling. In addition, this initial molecular dissection revealed that an inhibitory pathway involving NF-ΞΊB is triggered by this quinazoline-based Ξ±1-adrenoceptor antagonist. Several signalling mechanisms are likely to be involved in a molecular crosstalk, such as the Smad activation and inhibition of the antiapoptotic effects of NF-ΞΊB. Ongoing studies are focused on further characterisation of these pathways and the functional significance of the overexpressed genes in specimens from doxazosin-treated patients. This will provide the molecular basis for assessing the potential therapeutic significance of quinazoline monotherapy in androgen-independent prostate cancer.
</sections.7>

